## Verified findings (source @ HEAD `791030d721`, branch `hotfix`)

The filter chain lives in `VehicleAngularVelocity::FilterAngularVelocity()` at
`src/modules/sensors/vehicle_angular_velocity/VehicleAngularVelocity.cpp:725-768`. Each axis runs
through this exact sequence:

1. **Dynamic notch — ESC RPM** (`:729-740`) — `_dynamic_notch_filter_esc_rpm[h][axis][esc].applyArray(data, N)`; only if the array is allocated and `getNotchFreq() > 0`. Enabled by `IMU_GYRO_DNF_EN` bit 0.
2. **Dynamic notch — FFT peaks** (`:742-749`) — `_dynamic_notch_filter_fft[axis][peak].applyArray(data, N)`; only if `_dynamic_notch_fft_available`. Enabled by `IMU_GYRO_DNF_EN` bit 1.
3. **Static notch 0** (`:753-756`) — `_notch_filter0_velocity[axis].applyArray(data, N)`; only if `getNotchFreq() > 0`, i.e. `IMU_GYRO_NF0_FRQ > 0` (default 0 — disabled).
4. **Static notch 1** (`:758-761`) — `_notch_filter1_velocity[axis].applyArray(data, N)`; only if `IMU_GYRO_NF1_FRQ > 0` (default 0 — disabled).
5. **Low-pass biquad** (`:764`) — `_lp_filter_velocity[axis].applyArray(data, N)`; **always** applied; cutoff `IMU_GYRO_CUTOFF` (default 40 Hz).

**Answer: all four notch stages run first; the low-pass is last.**

**Why this order (standard signal-processing rationale):** notches need to attack the original
narrow-band peaks (motor/ESC vibration, FFT-detected resonances) at their full amplitude. Running
the broadband LPF first would attenuate and phase-shift the very peaks the notches are tuned to
cancel, hurting their effectiveness, and would also add LPF group delay before the notches see the
signal.

**Bonus — angular acceleration (D-term) path.** `FilterAngularAcceleration()` at `:770-782`
back-differences the **pre-LPF (raw) gyro** (`data[n] - _angular_velocity_raw_prev`) and then runs
that through a separate alpha low-pass at `IMU_DGYRO_CUTOFF` — so the published
`vehicle_angular_velocity.xyz_derivative` is NOT a numerical derivative of the LPF'd `xyz`. This is
already documented in `imu_clarification_2026-05-14.*` §3.2 and FAQ.

